                  </persName>
            . I am an apprentice to Mr. 
               <persName id="t18150510-12-person175">
                  William 
                  Ryde
               <interp inst="t18150510-12-person175" type="surname" value="Ryde"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person175" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person175" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t18150510-12-person176">
                  Thomas 
                  Vincent
               <interp inst="t18150510-12-person176" type="surname" value="Vincent"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person176" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person176" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , they are <rs id="t18150510-12-viclabel69" type="occupation">wholesale grocers</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18150510-12-victim171 t18150510-12-viclabel69"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18150510-12-victim173 t18150510-12-viclabel69"></join> in Cannon-street; the prisoner has been their <rs id="t18150510-12-deflabel70" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18150510-12-defend169 t18150510-12-deflabel70"></join> about seven or eight months. On the 28th of March, I went to his house, between two and three o'clock in the middle of the day; I found him at home and no one else; on my going into his house; I found the prisoner sitting on a bag and under his apron, I thought I saw something white, I wished to send him on an errand; on his raising up, I asked him what he had under his apron I went to him with the intention of sending him out, I took from him what he had under his apron; it proved to be a bag containing white pepper, a canvas bag containing nine pounds; I took it from him, and sent him out of an errand, on his return back he said he had found this bag in a corner. I told him he must take it to our house; we had a cask of white pepper, we examined it, and found the cask deficient thirty pounds weight. The pepper in the bag, is precisely the same as in the cask; I have<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181505100014"></xptr>not the least doubt that the pepper was taken out of the cask. The value is about twenty seven shillings, I gave it to the parish officer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150510-12-person177">
                  JAMES 
                  DOMVILLE
               <interp inst="t18150510-12-person177" type="surname" value="DOMVILLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person177" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150510-12-person177" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I received the bag of pepper from Mr. Moody; it has been in my possession ever since.</p>
